XIV. From what has been said, it may be collected, how unsafe it is for a private Christian man to inflict punishment, and especially capital punishment, either for the sake of his own or of the public good, upon a guilty person3 although, as we have said, that is some- times permittes] by the Law of Nations. And hence we must approve of the usage of those peoples by whom navigators are provided with commissions from the public power to suppress pirates, if they find any upon the seas 3 on which commissions they may act, not as of their own motion, but by public command.

XV. Of much the same kind is the provision which prevails in many places, that not any body who chooses can take up the accusa- tion of crimes, but only certain persons on whom that office is imposed by the public power 3 so that no one shall do any thing to shed the blood of another, except by the necessity of his office. Accordingly the canon of the Council of Seville provides, that if any one of the faith- ful shall turn informer, and by his means any one shall be proscribed or put to death, he shall not receive the Communion, even when

dying.
